One of Dmitry Galkovsky's more zany theories is that artists in Europe drew inspiration from discovered art left from Antiquity depicting the titanides, the female titan giantesses, so it ended up influencing the female nude form down to the ones we see in Rembrandt and Rubens.

Sort of like if Soviet art had been really good and after an apocalypse 1000 years later people discovered depictions of female workers in collective farms drawn with thick developed forearms and then started drawing all women that way

My favorite part in Don Quixote has always been when Sancho Panza becomes governor as a joke and then suddenly turns out to be very good at that office and Galkovsky made the point this is a very unique episode in early literature because here what is parodied is reality itself.

The rest of Don Quixote makes fun of the chivalric romantism, idealistic books, naive readers, etc. but here suddenly Sancho suddenly turns out to be a real wise ruler completely overturning and subverting the joke and it turns out "realism" itself is out of touch and delusional.

"Reality is constantly bifurcated and self-parodied."
